Message-ID: <3E14DABD-1733-47A8-A706-62A1A4C7E24A@gmail.com>

This has been rehashed several times over the years... 

One aspect, which is often overlooked is that all factors have orderINGs even when they are not orderED. This controls how you print them, tabulate them, which level is the baseline for treatment contrasts, etc. So you do need a way to access the position in the ordering for a given factor level. (People who blindly convert factors to character may realize that their analyses come out different depending on the collating sequence of the current locale. Or just find that their graphs come out with Month sorted alphabetically.)

A related issue that has bugged me "forever" is that we treat ordered factors as if their levels are equidistant even when that is patently untrue. The use of polynomial contrasts for ordered factors reflects this - it would really be more sensible to use e.g. successive differences or (ick!) Helmert contrasts for the ordered case and reserve poly() for factors with actual numerical levels. To me, this effectively makes ordered factors conceptually useless.  

- Peter D.

